141.1. id esse fatum. Comp. note on 1, 20, 55. Chrysippus’s defi· nition in Eusebius Pr. Ev. VI, 7, 13 runs thus: τὸ ἀπαράβατον καὶ ἐξ αἰῶνος καθῆκον τῶν αἰτιῶν, ὅσα οὑτωσὶ κατηναγκάσθε γενέσθαι, καὶ ὃσα ἄλλως ἔχειν κεκώλυται.

141. 4. fissum iecoris: probably a fissure or cut separating the dif- serent lobes of the liver, called limes in Seneca OEd. 365. The fissure denoted good or evil fortune according to the circumstances; there was a fissum vitale, a fissum familiare, and other similar sorts. See De Div. ΙΙ, 6, 12.13; Brisson. De Form. 1, 31; Miiller Etrusk. II, 182.

141. 4. sortls, such as were used in the temple of Fortuna at Prae· neste for divination; they were counters, which when mixed like a pack of cards were thrown into a vase, and one or more were drawn out. Hense the expressions sortes aequore, sortem ducere or trahere. Comp. De Div. 1, 18, 343 ΙΙ, 33, 703 41, 96; Suet. Tiber. 14. The sortes were not all of the same kind, and those expressions do not have the same mean· ing with all.
